{
  "answer": "**The central image in Allama Iqbal's \"Ghurra-e-\" (Bang-e-Dara Part 3, Chapter 8) is the crescent moon (or new moon) of Shawwal, known as the Eid crescent, which signals the end of Ramadan fasting and the arrival of Eid al-Fitr.**[^1]\n\nThis poem personifies the crescent as a luminous witness to the Muslim ummah's past glory and current decline. It directly addresses the crescent—\"O, crescent of Shawwal, light to the fasting eye\"—urging it to appear while commanding it to \"behold\" scenes of division, loss, and forgotten pride among Muslims, contrasting with its own serene freedom.[^2][^3]\n\n[^1]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 3*, Chapter 8: \"Ghurra-e-\", [paragraph](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-3-cc61e8/08-ghurra-e/translation/#p-13a49b).\n[^2]: Ibid., [paragraphs](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-3-cc61e8/08-ghurra-e/translation/#p-0d32d9).\n[^3]: Ibid., [chapter](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-3-cc61e8/08-ghurra-e/translation/).",
